tin personal name <i>Buccius</i> (presumably a derivative of <i>bucca</i> ‘mouth’) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","English: variant of   Boosey  .","Americanized form of German   Busse  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bessey","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Suffolk): perhaps a variant of   Bussey  .","French: habitational name from any of the places in Côte-d'Or and Loire named Bessey, from the Gallo-Roman estate <i>Bassiacum</i>, from the Roman personal name <i>Bassius</i> + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>."]},{"name":"Boosey","meanings":["(2010: NA)","English: topographic name from Middle English <i>bosy</i> ‘ox-stall, cow-stall’ (Old English <i>bōsig</i>)."]},{"name":"Bussie","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Bussey  , of Norman origin. This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Bucey","meanings":["English: probably a variant of   Bussey  ."]},{"name":"Busey","meanings":["English: variant of   Bussey  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"William D Bussey was born in 1175, in England, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Hugh Bussey. He had at least 1 son with Rose or Roesia Fitz baldwin de Clare."},"et":{"1175–":"1175–Surnud","1175–Male":"1175–Surnud","1175–Female":"